First off, it wasn't clear that it was assessing "risk of demonstrating features of" PD. Obviously, this was already measuring features of PD - probability is not a correct outcome measure here. Second, severity is frightening no matter what it says afterward, and "Severity: Severe" is entirely  meaningless. You could say that the task showed similarity to that observed in PD, a match level of sort (after all, your score is based on what is seen in a large dataset of patients of a similar demo, not an absolute PD measure). Third, moving and flashing objects are a no-no: if the person being tested actually does have PD, then they are going to be distracted. And if the results are a high match for PD, you don't want the screen to look like they won a prize at a carnival.

Getting the diagnosis and summary of factors that led to the diagnosis doesn't help the patient feel empowered or in control of health; the patient needs to know the next steps (i.e. See a neurologist.  Exercise.  Eat a Mediterranean diet.  Perhaps join a support group or check out an organization like Davis Phinney.)

A PD diagnosis is scary. It's not clear how much the user taking the test will have been briefed about PD before the test is given and how quickly the user will be advised of next steps. If PD is "likely" the user should be immediately informed that there are proactive steps that can be taken to slow progression/reduce symptoms over several years. I'm sure there's a more concise way to say that but you get the idea: provide hope and reassurance and specific next steps.

Also, there doesn't seem to be any purpose for giving the tiered results by task. Think about what you want the user to take away from this page. Why would he/she care about relative performance in each task area? I don't think you should tell anyone that a symptom is "severe" without a coach present to explain why this is important to the user, e.g., how it effects prognosis or treatment, including strong recommendations for an exercise program, diet and sleep.
